default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultJ
defaultust because most cases are withdrawn b
defaultefore a full hearing does not mean they are without merit - a significant number of cases are withdrawn because they settle in favour of the
default claimant before reaching court.
default Often it is the threat of judicial review which prompts public authorities to prov
defaultide solutions, but not before substantial work has been done. So cases which are likely to settle at an early stage are often some of the strongest cases. It is no exaggeration to say that legal aid for judicial review can be the only thing standing betwee
defaultn a homeless family and the street.
default&#xa0;
defaultExamples of the type of cases in which the Judicial Review process is of real benefit to bureaux clients include:- 
default&#xa0;
defaultA client came to their local CAB after their homelessness application had been turned down by their council despite the fact they had 
defaultno where
default to live and was suffering from a  serious lung condition.  Not only did the council turn down the application but
default they also refused to house the client while their decision was reviewed.  The CAB took action to get a 
defaultlegal aid counsel opinion that they would be able to make an application for judicial review.  With the threat of this judicial review the council agree
defaultd to
default&#xa0;
defaultprovide accommodation pending review.  With the CAB and Counsel's opinion supporting the client, the
default&#xa0;
defaultreview
default&#xa0;
defaultfound in their favour
default&#xa0;
defaultthat
default&#xa0;
defaultthey were in need of support to avoid homelessness and there was no need for a court hearing.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIf the council
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaulthad k
defaultnown that the CAB could not afford to take it further they
default&#xa0;
defaultmay have been less likely to bow to pressure.
default&#xa0;
defaultWithout the threat of a judicial review a
default CAB
default client
default in 
defaultLancashire
