defaultReform of the 
defaultCriminal Legal Aid Market
default and Fees
default&#xa0;
defaultCriminal legal aid is not our area of expert
defaultise so we do not intend to comment 
defaultin detail 
defaulton these issues;
default however 
defaultmany of our advisors
default regularly report circumstances in which vulnerable individuals are unable to get appropriate legal support
default in magistrates or county court 
defaultproceedings
default.
default 
defaultWhilst we are 
default 
defaultoften
default able to advise social welfare matters 
defaultwe
default do not have the expertise to advise or represent in 
defaultcomplex 
defaultfamily cases, and certainly not in any criminal law proceedings. For example:-
default              
defaultA CAB in the South West was visited by a single parent with a disabl
defaulted son, who had recently 
default              
defaultbeen made redundant and was in the process of claiming Income Support and Carer's 
default              
defaultAllowance. She needed legal representation in the Magistrate's court for a drink driving case. 
default              
defaultShe had strong mitigating circumstances as she was 
defaultthe victim of an assault at the time and 
default              
defaultwas moving away from the house of the attacker, by moving her car 50 yards. She was told by 
default              
defaultseveral solicitors that she was not eligible for legal aid and the cost would be several thousand 
default              
defaultpounds, although they 
defaultall thought she had a case to argue. She was desperate for help 
default              
default              
defaultbecause she could not afford to lose her licence with a disabled child. When she visited the 
default              
defaulther local CAB
default, the case was due to come to court in three weeks time
default&#xa0;
defaultWhilst we welcome that the
default government have abandoned a potentially unworkable procurement model for criminal defence services, we remain concerned that a 17.5% cut will be impossible for suppliers to absorb. Many more firms will exit legal aid or close as a result which will also h
defaultave a knock on impact on the supply of civil and family legal aid meaning there will be less support for the overworked CAB service. 
defaultReforming Fees in Civil Legal Aid
default&#xa0;
defaultWe disagree with the proposed further fee reduction in family legal aid cases by 10 per
default cent
default.  Fees have already been 
defaultcut by 10 per cent under the LASPO reform package
default and the full implications of 
defaultthis may not have yet been felt
default. 
defaultCitizens Advice 
defaultBureaux rely heavily on being able to refer clients to local firms of solicitors fo
defaultr advice and r
defaultepresentation in f
defaultamily matters, and we are concerned
default that 
default this proposal which will weaken the supplier base and may lead 
defaultto some firms withdrawing from f
defaultamily legal aid altogether
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are also concerned that providers have 
defaultrecently 
defaultsigned new f
defaultamily con
defaulttracts, which started on 1 April 2013
default based on current fee levels.  Beyond any immediate unfairness of this, we are concerned that in future providers will have reduced con
defaultfidence in the tender process,
default damaging the supplier base for legal aid in general.
default&#xa0;
defaultExpert feesdefault&#xa0;
defaultWe would be concerned that
default the effect of a 20 per cent across the board cut risks experts being less attracted to appearing in cases funded by legal aid.
default 
defaultOften cases rely heavily on the availability of expert evidence.  If legal aid providers are unable to find experts willing to undertake the work at significantly reduced fees, clients will suffer. 
